th immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access. Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation. Drawing on evidence from around the world, he illustrates how the internet of things can be used to repress and control people. Yet he also demonstrates that if we actively engage with the governments and businesses building the internet of things, we have a chance to build a new kind of internet—and a more open society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElectronic surveillance. 0aInformation technologyxPolitical aspects. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 0aPrivacy, Right of. 0aTechnological innovationsxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019947540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021366940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213669/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY